{"/service/ndnp/iune/batch_iune_bismuth_ver01/data/sn2008060406/00332898188/1930110101/0731.xml":{"full_text":"THS BEER AND WL1E FALLACY\nJeer Amendment to Liquor L-iws\nWould be the End of Prohibition;\n2.75 Beer is Intoxicating\nWet newspapers have been making\nmuch of a statement attributed to Prof.\nLanripll Henderson, of the department of\nphysiology. Vale university. The professor\nis quoted as follows:\n\u201cNo beverage which ir\u00bb common usage is\ndrunk only in such amounts that not\nmore than the equivalent of eighty cubic\ncen'imentcrs of absolute alcohol is ab\nsorbed into the blocd an hour, can prop\nerly be denominated as intoxicating.\n\u201cGeneral experience shows that few\npersons care to drink two liters (half a\ngalloni of beer in an hour. Under this\ndefinition, therefore, beer containing 3 or\n4 per cent alcohol by volume is not intox\nicating A person who fs accustom\u00b0d to\ndrinking beer docs not become intoxicated\nin the proper sense of the word even if in\neach of several successive hours he drinks\na liter of 4 per cent beer.\u201d\nThis statement has >riven rise to ''di\ntorinVs advocating amendment of the Vol\nstead law to permit the sale of such\n\u201charmless\u201d beverages.\nWhen a lone professor makes a state\nment like the above, it is considered good\ncopy bv the wet press, though the real\nscientific findings and outstanding au\nthorities on the subject are to the con\ntrary.\nA book might be filled with practical\nand scientific t^i\u2019monv all a^reein^: with\nthe statement of Dr. Eugene Lyman Fisk,\nof the r,ife Ex^nsion Institute, who says:\n\u201cAlcohol is o\u2019eohol. either in whisky nr\nbeer. Tt is non\u00abens'' to claim that beer is\na hvdenic drink. It is drunk chiefiv for i's\nalcoholic effect, and if the alcoholic ef\nfect is produc'd the danger of alcohol ex\nists Any on\"' who doubts that, be^r nn\nproduce a cr\u201d*tfdn form of intoxication\nneed nnlv visit the saloon and watch the\nbeer drinker in various \u00abJa\"es of Kefud\ndlem'mt or excitement. If beer does not\nintoxicate or produce anv alcoholic effect,\nwhat becomes of the \u2018racial craving for\nstimulants\u2019 wtuch it is -said to satisfy?\nFurthermore, heavy ben- drinking, as in\nthe ease of brewery emnlovees. adds the\ndanger of excessive fluid infake. entirely\na Dart from alcohol .The b^avy mortality\nof brewery emnlovees is sufficient evidence\n(hat beer, so far as its e'fect noon live\nmasses of men is concerned, is not a hy\ngienic drink.\u201d\nDr. Harvev Wilev. food and dru\" ex\npert. testifying before the New Jersey\nled'-\u2019ature in 1020 and in a letter dated\nAnril 7. 1023. pave his onininn as follows:\n\u201cAn alcoholic content of 2.75 per cent, by\nweight, is equivalent to 3.45 per cent by\nvolume. There is no question in the mind\nof any informed person in regard to the\ntoxity of such a beer. It may not and does\nnot produce violent intoxication in most\npersons, but it does produce intoxication\nin every person. Those who are more sus\nceptible take on the form of intoxication\nwell known as drunkenness. Others per\nhaps do not exhibit symptoms which\nwould call attention to an intoxicated\nstate, except after drinking large quanti\nties. As beer is frequently drunk in large\nquantities by beer users, sometimes\namounting to 10 or 20 or even 30 or 40\nglasses a day, it is entirely possible that\nan alcoholic content of 2.75 per cent, by\nweight, would keep a person who would\nindulge in from 20 to 30 glasses a day in\na constant state of intoxication. Others\nmore susceptible would be visibly intoxi\ncated by a loss number of glasses, and all\nwho would drink it would be intoxicated\nby a less number of glasses, and all who\nwould drink it would be intoxicated to a\ncertain extent by a single glass.\n\u201cThe present limit on alcoholic content\nin the Volstead act is the only safe one\nto adopt if we propose to obey the limi\ntations fixed by the Eighteenth Amend\nment.\u201d\nThe United States Statistical Abstract\nfor 1920. page 561, gives the following fig\nures, showing the total consumption by\ngallons per capita of distilled spirits,\nwines and malt liquors for the vear 1918:\nPer capita consumption of dis\ntilled spirits .89\nPer capita consumption of wines. .49\nPer capita consumption of malt\nliquors 14.80\nPer capita consumption of all liq\nuors and wines 16.18\nTHE SLIPPERY PATH TO ANARCHY\n(From an address by Hon. William Gibbs McAdoo before the American Bar Association)\nThe inevitable logic of the repeal by a state of its prohibition enforcement laws or the\nrefusal by a state to perforin its constitutional duty to enact such laws is nullification,\nopen and undisguised, of the constitution of the United States. It is to the active and\nunabashed campaign in favor of nullification that I wish to call your attention as a part,\nand a very fundamental part, of the broader problem of law and order which I mentioned\nat the beginning of this address. It is a campaign to induce the people of this country to\naccomplish results not by lawful means or by following the due course of law. but by\nopenly and frankly violating and disregarding the highest law of the land. If this method\nof accomplishing results is to be pursued in the case of prohibition, there is no valid\nreason why any other provision of the constitution may not be similarly disregarded and\nnullified. The Eighteenth Amendment is as much a part of the constitution as any other\nclause or section of it. and is entitled to as much respect, no more and no less, as any\noilier clause or section. Constitutional govt .nment is impossible if we proceed on the\nprinciple that only those parts of the constitution arc to be observed and enforced which\nany given state or individual happens to like or approve. This is the slippery path which\nleads to anarchy. It is the negation of the principle of majority rule; it sets up that very\ntyranny of the minority which the opponents of prohibition assail so loudly.\nADVOCATES OF LAWLESSNESS\nThe campaign to secure nullification of the constitution by action of the state gov\nernments is only one part, although a very significant part, of the widespread advocacy\nof lawlessness by the opponents of prohibition. Supporters of the Eighteenth Amendment\nare not engaged in lawlessness. They are yielding obedience to the constitution and laws.\nIf those who oppose prohibition would yield the same measure of obedience, there would\nbe no prohibition question. Not only do they refuse obedience, but they do not stop with\nattempting to establish nullification by state aetion; they are engaged in a vast propa\ngandist enterprise to secure nullification by the private acts of individuals. For this pur\npose. men of prominence and standing are advancing arguments which they would, no\ndoubt, be the first to condemn if they proceeded from some ignorant anarchist or com\nmunist fresh from the oppressions of old-world tyranny, and excusable for not yet un\nderstanding the principles of constitutional government.\nThese official figures show that of the\nsixteen gallons per capita of alcoholic\nbevei'ages consumed, almost fifteen gal\nlons were beer. Less than one gallon was\nwhisky.\nWould these beer pleaders have the peo\nple believe that the drunkenness and law\n]essness which centered in the 177,000 sa\nloons of that day\u2014so flagrant that the\npeople rose in their might and overthrew\nthe traffic\u2014would they have the people\nbelieve that these evils were all the result\nof the per capita consumption of less than\none gallon of whisky and not of the per\ncapita consumption of almost fifteen gal\nlons of beer?\nMoreover, beer as a substitute for pro\nhibition has been put to the test, and has\nutterly failed. For examples Massachu\nsetts tried a beer experiment. In 1869, the\nstate was dry. In 1870, a new law permit\nted towns that wished to sell beer, cider,\nporter and ale. A typical example of what\nhappened is New Bedford where, in the\nyear in which the beer saloons were\nopened. 1872, crime rose 68 per cent and\narrests for drunkenness 120 per cent. It\ndid not work.\nHamlett Bates, police justice. Chelsea,\nMass., said, on January 3. 1873: \u201cThe sale\nof beer should not be legalized. Almost\nevery beer saloon is a rum-shop.\"\nGeorgia tried a beer experiment from\n1908 to 1916. Distilled liquors could not be\nsold in saloons, only light or near-beer.\nJudge Broyles, then of the police court\nof Atlanta, said: \u201cA light or near-beer\nlaw is practically unenforceable, as you\nrannot, have a chemist with every barrel\nto see that the beer is light. Any beer\nwill be sold. Besides, men do get drunk on\n2 ner cent beer if they take enough of it.\"\nIn answer to a suggestion that the light\nwines and beer be legalized Wm. Howard\nTaft, said:\n\u201cI am not in favor of amending the\nVolstead act in respect to the amount of\npermissible alcohol in beverages. I am not\nin favor of allowing light wines and beer\nto be sold under the Eighteenth Amend\nment. I believe it would defeat the pur\npose of the amendment. No such distinc\ntion as that between wines and beer on\nthe one hand and spirituous liquors on\nthe other is practicable as a police meas\nure. Any such loophole as light wines and\nbeer would make the amendment a\nlaughing stock.\u201d\nAnother reason why a beer amendment\nto our prohibition laws is unthinkable is\nbecause the drinking of beer is the begin\nning of the liquor habit. The beginner\nfirst drinks beer, then when the alcoholic\ncontent in beer no longer contains a suf\nficient \"kick,\u201d whisky and the other ar\ndent liquors are resorted to. Mr. William\nC. Hollister, member of the board of di\nrectors of the Washingtonian Home,\nwhich before prohibition was the largest\nsingle institution in the country treating\nvictims of the liquor traffic, says: \u2018For\nforty years I have been in close touch\nwith its work of reclaiming drunkards.\nThis liquor cure was established in 1863.\nI have talked with hundreds of its pa\ntients. All began with beer and wine and\nbecame whisky addicts.\u201d\n\u201cTHE VALUE OF LAW OBSERVANCE\u201d\nGovernment Issues Educational\nBooklet on Prohibition\nThe department of justice, bureau of\nprohibition, lias just issued a 57-page\nbooklet entitled, \u201cThe Value of Law Ob\nservance.\u201d It contains in succinct form\nauthentic facts, figures, and argument on\nthe evils of liquor drinking, and the value\nto society of prohibiting the traffic.\nThe following on the effect of alcohol\non the community and on crime are typi\ncal of the excellent material contained in\nthis educational booklet issued by the gov\nernment itself:\nTHE EFFECT OF ALCOHOL ON\nTHE COMMUNITY\nAlcohol effects primarily the nervous\nsystem. It reacts on the protoplasm of\nthe body, entering the blood stream as\nsoon as it is taken into the body. Its ef\nfects may be compared to the effect of a\nriver running through its bed. While a\nwatercourse in a mountain stream flowing\nthrough rocks will alter the bed of a\nstream only after a long time, where a\nriver flows through sand or gravel, the\nchanges are noted suddenly and con\ntinuously.\nSo, while the effect of alcohol on one\nman\u2019s constitution may be slow and hard\nto trace, and show no definite results over\na period of time, the effect upon another\u2019s\nconstitution will be observed almost im\nmediately and the changes before the in\ndividual dies will be spectacular.\nAlcohol attacks in the body, first, the\nlatest developed and most complex tis\nsues, the nerve cells of the gray cortex of\nthe brain, the cells directly associated\nwith the exhibition of mental processes.\nIt is here that the religionist and the\nmoralist has a splendid opportunity of\nBANK SAVINGS AT NEW PEAK DESPITE BUSINESS DEPRESSION\n(Chicago Herald and Examiner)\nIn the midst of the business depression, savings deposits of banks and trust com\npanies in the United States have set a new high mark, the American Banker\u2019s Associa\ntion reveals.\nIn the year ended June 30. 1930, savings deposits of these institutions in continental\nUnited States increased $267,180,000, reaching $28,485,000,000, the highest point ever re\ncorded.\nThis contrasts with a decline in savings of $195,305,000 in the previous year.\nThe total number of depositors reported at the end of June 30,1930, was 52,769,175, a\ngain of 5,048 over a year ago.\ndiscussing the detrimental effect upon th*\nmorals of the persons who consume it.\nWaiving this line of approach for tho\nreason above mentioned, we may look for\nthe effect on the community in the im\npairment of both body and mind. Cumu\nlative poisoning symptoms are apparent\nin the persons under observation.\nTaking the United States as a whole,\n30 per cent of the inmates of institutions\nduring the year 1909 showed alcoholic\nparentage. Edinburgh reported 42 per\ncent; England. 50 per cent; Paris, 23 per\ncent; Vienna, 31 per cent; Germany, 32\nper cent: Prussia, in 1880, 30 per cent; in\n1886, 35 per cent; in 1887. 36 per cent; in\n1888, 40 per cent; in 1903, 45 per cent.\nIn the Craig colony for epileptics, in\nNew York, in 1910. the causes of epilepsy\nin 469 inmates was heredity, and in 213\ndirectly traceable to alcoholism acquired\nby the patients and 259 showed alcoholic\nparents.\nIt may be stated that a study of mental\ndiseases the world over shows that 25 to\n50 per cent can be traced directly to alco\nholism on the part of the patient or to\nalcoholic parentage.\nThe advantage and value ofnational\nprohibition law observance to the com\nmunity cannot be denied.\nALCOHOL AND CRIME\nA lord chief justice of England states:\n\u201cIf thoroughly examined, nine-tenths of\nthe crimes of England and Wales could\nbe traced to drink.\u2019\u2019\nThe Massachusetts Bureau of Labor\nStatistics showed in 1905 that 84 per cent\nof ail criminals under conviction in cor\nrectional institutions of that state owed\nthe conditions which induced the crime to\nintemperate habits.\nA committee investigating crime in the\nUnited States in 1900 concluded that 49.95\nper cent of the criminals in the country\nwere induced to commit crimes by alco\nholism.\nCrime investigations in countries whose\nreputation is that of light drinking are\nas follows:\nDUE TO ALCOHOL PER CENT\nGermany 41.7\nAustria 58.3\nFrance 60\nIt is stated by students of criminology\nthat alcoholism is responsible for CO per\ncent of the antisocial propensities that\nmake necessary jails and correctional in\nstitutions.\nIn addition to this. 20 to 35 per cent\nof the inmates in state poorliouses indi\ncate an alcoholic history.\nThus it is shown that alcohol is respon\nsible\u2019 for at least 25 per cent of the in\nsane in the United States; for 40 per cent\nof the neglected or abandoned children in\nthe United States; for 50 per cent of the\nconvicts in prisons; for 80 per cent of the\ninmates of jails and workhouses; a large\nnumber of suicides and accidents; almost\nall veneral diseases: and a large propor\ntion of me.rital infelicities.\nIt is well to point out that these figures\nwere all collected before the national pro\nhibition act became effective in 1920.\nILLINOIS DRYER NOT WETTER\n(Continued from Page 1)\nfor my purpose. Any man can say that,\nwho does not see anything wrong in\nslavery; but no man can logically say it\nwho does see a wrong in it, because no\nman can logically say he don\u2019t care\nwhether a wrong is voted up or voted\ndown. He may say he don\u2019t care whether\nan indifferent thing is voted up or down;\nbut he must logically have a choice be\ntween a right thing and a wrong thing.\nHe contends that whatever community\nwants slaves has a right to have them. So\nthey have, if it is not wrong. But if it is a\nwrong, he cannot say people have a right\nto do wrong. He says that upon the score\nof equality, slaves should be allowed to\ngo into a new territory, like other prop\nerty. If it and other property are equal,\nhis argument is entirely logical. But if\nyou insist that one is wrong and the other\nright, there is no use to institute a com\nparison between right and wrong.\n\u201cThat is the issue that will continue in\nthis country when these poor tongues of\nJudge Douglas and myself shall be silent.\nIt Is the eternal struggle between these\nprinciples\u2014right and wrong\u2014throughout\nthe world. They are the two principles\nthat have stood face to face from the be\nginning of time, and will ever continue to\nstruggle.\u201d","height":"18180","width":"14064"}}
